{"award_age":79.0,"bio_image":"full\/c98b3190dd6e8f1d414908c0321cdde143f9a183.jpg","category":"Literature","country":"Spain","date_of_birth":"1898-04-26T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1984-12-13T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/2\/2f\/Vicentealeixandre.jpg\/260px-Vicentealeixandre.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vicente_Aleixandre","mini_bio":"<p><b>Vicente P\u00edo Marcelino Cirilo Aleixandre y Merlo<\/b> (April 26, 1898 \u2013 December 14, 1984) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Spain\" title=\"Spain\">Spanish<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Poet\" title=\"Poet\">poet<\/a> who was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Seville\" title=\"Seville\">Seville<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vicente_Aleixandre#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Aleixandre received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Literature\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Literature\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Literature<\/a> in 1977 \"for a creative poetic writing which illuminates man's condition in the cosmos and in present-day society, at the same time representing the great renewal of the traditions of Spanish poetry between the wars\". He was part of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Generation_of_%2727\" title=\"Generation of '27\">Generation of '27<\/a>.<\/p><p>Aleixandre's early poetry, which he wrote mostly in free verse, is highly <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Surrealism\" title=\"Surrealism\">surrealistic<\/a>. It also praises the beauty of nature by using symbols that represent the earth and the sea. Many of Aleixandre's early poems are filled with sadness. They reflect his feeling that people have lost the passion and free spirit that he saw in nature.<\/p><p>He died in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Madrid\" title=\"Madrid\">Madrid<\/a> in 1984.<\/p><p>His early collections of poetry include <i>Passion of the Earth<\/i> (1935) and <i>Destruction or Love<\/i> (1933). In 1944, he wrote <i>Shadow of Paradise<\/i>, the poetry where he first began to concentrate on themes such as fellowship, friendliness, and spiritual unity. His later books of poetry include <i>History of the Heart<\/i> (1954) and <i>In a Vast Dominion<\/i> (1962).<\/p><p>Aleixandre studied law at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Complutense_University_of_Madrid\" title=\"Complutense University of Madrid\">University of Madrid<\/a>. Selections of his work were translated into English in <i>Twenty Poems of Vicente Aleixandre<\/i> (1977) and <i>A Longing for the Light: Selected Poems of Vincent Aleixandre<\/i> (1979; <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Copper_Canyon_Press\" title=\"Copper Canyon Press\">Copper Canyon Press<\/a>, 2007) (translated by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lewis_Hyde\" title=\"Lewis Hyde\">Lewis Hyde<\/a>).<\/p>","name":"Vicente Aleixandre","place_of_birth":"Seville ,  Spain","place_of_death":"Madrid ,  Spain","text":"Vicente Aleixandre , Literature, 1977","year":1977.0}